[5] South Korea, 11 cases - WHO 30 May 2015, RFI
Date: 30 May 2015
Source: Global Alert and Response Disease Outbreak News 30 May 2015 [edited]
http://who.int/csr/don/30-may-2015-mers-korea/en/


Middle East respiratory syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) - Republic of Korea 30 May 2015
----------------------
Between 26 and 29 May 2015, the National IHR Focal Point of the Republic of Korea notified WHO of additional confirmed cases of Middle East Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus (MERS-CoV). This DON describes the 8 additional cases and provides an update on the 3 cases of MERS-CoV infection reported in a previous DON on 24 May [2015].

Details of the cases are as follows:

1 - The 1st case was reported in the DON of 24 May [2015]. The patient is a 68-year-old male with the following travel history: [18-29 Apr 2015], Bahrain; [29-30 Apr 2015], United Arab Emirates; [30 Apr 2015 to 1 May 2015], Bahrain; 1-2 May [2015], the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia; 2 May [2015], Bahrain; and 2-3 May [2015], Qatar. He arrived at Incheon International airport via Qatar on 4 May [2015]. The patient was asymptomatic on arrival. He developed symptoms on 11 May [2015] and sought medical care at a local clinic from 12 to 15 May [2015]. The patient was then admitted to hospital on 15 May [2015] and discharged on 17 May [2015]. On the day of discharge, he went to another clinic. Between 17 and 20 May [2015], the patient visited another hospital. He tested positive for MERS-CoV on 20 May [2015] and was transferred to the nationally designated treatment facility for isolation. Currently, the patient is in stable condition. He has no history of exposure to known risk factors. Investigation of the source of infection is ongoing.

2- The 2nd case was reported in the DON of 24 May [2015]. The patient is a 64-year-old female who is the wife of the 1st case. She has no comorbidities. The patient did not travel abroad. She took care of her husband during his hospitalization from 15 May [2015]. The patient developed symptoms on 18 May [2015] and was transferred to the nationally designated medical centre. She tested positive for MERS-CoV on 20 May [2015]. Currently, the patient is in stable condition.

3- The 3rd case was reported in the DON of 24 May [2015]. The patient is a 76-year-old male who shared a hospital room with the 1st case on 16 May [2015]. He developed symptoms on 20 May [2015] and was transferred to the nationally designated medical centre. The patient tested positive for MERS-CoV on the same day. Currently, he is in stable condition.

4- The 4th case is a 46-year-old female who is the daughter of the 3rd case. The patient took care of her father during his hospitalization from 16 to 20 May [2015]. During this period, she shared the same room with the 1st case. The patient had been under monitoring since 21 May [2015] and developed symptoms on 25 May [2015]. She was transferred to the nationally designated medical centre and tested positive for MERS-CoV on 25 May [2015]. Currently, the patient is in stable condition.

5- The 5th case is a 50-year-old male health professional who treated the 1st case on 17 May [2015]. The patient had been self-isolated and under monitoring since 22 May [2015]. He developed symptoms on 25 May [2015] and was transferred to the nationally designated medical centre. He tested positive for MERS-CoV on 26 May [2015]. Currently, he is in stable condition.

6- The 6th case is a 71-year-old male who shared the same ward with the 1st case during his hospitalization from 15 to 17 May [2015]. The patient, who has comorbidities, developed symptoms on 24 May [2015] and visited an emergency department. He tested positive for MERS-CoV on 28 May [2015].

7- The 7th case is a 28-year-old female health professional who was involved in the 1st case's care between 16 and 17 May [2015]. Her self-isolation started from 21 May [2015] and she developed symptoms. As symptoms worsened, the patient was transferred to the nationally designated medical centre on 27 May [2015]. She tested positive for MERS-CoV on 28 May [2015]. The patient, who has no comorbidities, is currently in stable condition.

8- The 8th case is a 46-year-old female health professional who treated the 1st case on 15 May [2015]. The patient, who has no comorbidities, developed symptoms and was transferred to the nationally designated medical centre on 26 May [2015]. She tested positive for MERS-CoV on 29 May [2015]. Currently, the patient is in stable condition.

9- The 9th case is a 56-year-old male who shared the same ward with the 1st case during his hospitalization from 15 to 17 May [2015]. The patient had been hospitalized since 9 May [2015] for an unrelated medical condition. He tested positive for MERS-CoV on 29 May [2015].

10- The 10th case is a 79-year-old female who shared the same ward with the 1st case during his hospitalization from 15 to 17 May [2015]. The patient, who has comorbidities, developed symptoms on 20 May [2015] and was isolated on 28 May [2015]. She tested positive for MERS-CoV on 29 May [2015].

11- The 11th case is a 49-year-old female who shared the same ward with the 1st case during his hospitalization from 15 to 17 May [2015]. The patient, who has comorbidities, developed symptoms on 21 May [2015] and was isolated on 28 May [2015]. She tested positive for MERS-CoV on 29 May [2015].

Contact tracing of household contacts and healthcare contacts is ongoing for the cases.

Globally, WHO has been notified of 1147 laboratory-confirmed cases of infection with MERS-CoV, including at least 431 related deaths.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The 2 WHO reports above are helpful in detailing the confirmed cases through official data. It clarifies the current situation of the South Korea-related outbreak as presently representing 2 generations of infection as mentioned in my comment following section [1] above. It will be of interest to learn the postulated (or possibly documented) route of transmission in the hospital ward where much of the exposure/transmission appears to have occurred. Was the index case treated with nebulizers for respiratory compromise felt to be bronchospasm related? The use of nebulizers might have facilitated the aerosolization of infected/infective material and led to further spread in the ward environment. It will be of interest to see the physical layout of the ward, showing the location of the index case and of the secondary cases. - Mod.MPP]
